Customer Churn Data Exploration and Prediction¶

Goals¶

  • Understand the customers of our bank
  • Can a model be created to understand the causes of of customer churn and predict churning customers?

In [172]:
df.Attrition_Flag = df.Attrition_Flag.replace({'Attrited Customer':1,'Existing Customer':0})
df.Gender = df.Gender.replace({'F':1,'M':0})
df = pd.concat([df,pd.get_dummies(df['Education_Level']).drop(columns=['Unknown'])],axis=1)
df = pd.concat([df,pd.get_dummies(df['Income_Category']).drop(columns=['Unknown'])],axis=1)
df = pd.concat([df,pd.get_dummies(df['Marital_Status']).drop(columns=['Unknown'])],axis=1)
df = pd.concat([df,pd.get_dummies(df['Card_Category']).drop(columns=['Platinum'])],axis=1)
df.drop(columns = ['Education_Level','Income_Category','Marital_Status','Card_Category','CLIENTNUM'],inplace=True)

In [181]:
N_COMPONENTS = 4

pca_model = PCA(n_components = N_COMPONENTS )

pc_matrix = pca_model.fit_transform(ohe_data)

evr = pca_model.explained_variance_ratio_
total_var = evr.sum() * 100
cumsum_evr = np.cumsum(evr)

trace1 = {
    "name": "individual explained variance", 
    "type": "bar", 
    'y':evr}
trace2 = {
    "name": "cumulative explained variance", 
    "type": "scatter", 
     'y':cumsum_evr}
data = [trace1, trace2]
layout = {
    "xaxis": {"title": "Principal components"}, 
    "yaxis": {"title": "Explained variance ratio"},
  }
fig = go.Figure(data=data, layout=layout)
fig.update_layout(height=700, width=900, title='Explained Variance Using {} Dimensions'.format(N_COMPONENTS))
fig.show()

Approx 50% of the variance can be explained by PC-3¶

We'll use that as our limit moving forward

In [182]:
loadings = pca_model.components_.T  # Transpose to align with (features, components)

loadings_df = pd.DataFrame(loadings, columns=['PC-{}'.format(i) for i in range(N_COMPONENTS)], index=ohe_data.columns)

In [189]:
rf_pipe = Pipeline(steps =[ ('scale',StandardScaler()), ("RF",RandomForestClassifier(random_state=42)) ])
ada_pipe = Pipeline(steps =[ ('scale',StandardScaler()), ("RF",AdaBoostClassifier(random_state=42,learning_rate=0.7)) ])
svm_pipe = Pipeline(steps =[ ('scale',StandardScaler()), ("RF",SVC(random_state=42,kernel='rbf')) ])


f1_cross_val_scores = cross_val_score(rf_pipe,train_x,train_y,cv=5,scoring='f1')
ada_f1_cross_val_scores=cross_val_score(ada_pipe,train_x,train_y,cv=5,scoring='f1')
svm_f1_cross_val_scores=cross_val_score(svm_pipe,train_x,train_y,cv=5,scoring='f1')

TP = 1382
TN = 6386
FP = 2114
FN = 245

accuracy = (TP + TN) / (TP + TN + FP + FN)
precision = TP / (TP + FP)
recall = TP / (TP + FN)
f1_score = 2 * (precision * recall) / (precision + recall)

print('accuracy: ', accuracy) 
print('precision: ', precision) 
print('recall: ', recall) 
print('f1 score: ', f1_score)

accuracy:  0.7670583588426977
precision:  0.39530892448512583
recall:  0.8494161032575291
f1 score:  0.5395276205348429

Interpretation¶

  • The high recall indicates the model is good at catching actual churn cases but at the cost of a significant number of false positives, as reflected by the lower precision. This could mean the model tends to predict churn more often than it should.
  • The accuracy is relatively high, showing that the model performs well on this dataset. However, this metric can be misleading if the class distribution is imbalanced.
  • The F1 score provides a more balanced view of the model's performance, especially when dealing with imbalanced datasets.
    • A score around 54% suggests there's room for improvement, particularly in increasing precision without sacrificing recall too much.

Interpreting the AUC Values¶

Precision-Recall Curve of Class 0 (AUC = 0.972):¶

  • This is high, indicating that the model can identify the 'not churn' class with high precision and recall. However, since this is for class 0, it is less relevant as we're specifically interested in identifying churn (class 1)

Precision-Recall Curve of Class 1 (AUC = 0.635):¶

  • This value is moderate, reflecting the model's ability to identify the 'churn' class. A lower AUC for the positive class indicates the model struggles more with correctly predicting churn than not churn, particularly in terms of distinguishing between true positives and false positives across different thresholds

Micro-Average Precision-Recall Curve (AUC = 0.824):¶

  • The micro-average considers all classes and computes the average precision and recall across all thresholds. An AUC of 0.824 suggests that, overall, the model performs well in identifying both classes when aggregating the outcomes

Overall Assessment¶

  • The high AUC for the 'not churn' class and the overall micro-average suggest the model performs reasonably well overall, especially in distinguishing the negative cases
  • The moderate AUC for the 'churn' class indicates room for improvement in precisely identifying churn cases, which is critical for predicting churn
  • Given the importance of precisely identifying churn to allocate resources effectively or to intervene with customer retention strategies, focusing on improving the precision-recall balance for the churn class is important

Upsampling is a great way to normalise, but there can be issues with it....especially if our unknown is part of the minority class¶

Let's try undersampling, reducing the number of instances in our majority class¶

Need to reinitialise and ohe data once more to start fresh¶

trace1 = {
    "name": "individual explained variance", 
    "type": "bar", 
    'y':evr}

    "type": "scatter", 
     'y':cumsum_evr}

    "yaxis": {"title": "Explained variance ratio"},
  }

Interpreting the AUC Values¶

Precision-Recall Curve of Class 0 (AUC = 0.986):¶

  • No real change from the 'upsampling' result. Extremely effective at identifying customers who will not churn

Precision-Recall Curve of Class 1 (AUC = 0.763):¶

  • Undersampling actually increased the our model's ability to identify churning customers 🎉🎉🎉
  • Pretty happy with this considering the classes are imbalanced

Micro-Average Precision-Recall Curve (AUC = 0.905):¶

  • Huge increase from the upsampling model
  • The model performs well overall across both classes

Overall Assessment¶

  • Decently high scores across all metrics reflect well on the model's performance
  • After applying undersampling to address class imbalance, the scores show that the model is reliable in predicting non-churn and fairly effective at identifying churn
  • Techniques to further improve churn prediction could provide even more value

Feature importance for this model¶

Total_Trans_Ct (39.84% importance):¶

  • This is the most influential feature. It likely represents the total count of transactions made by a customer, which indicates that the frequency of transactions is a strong predictor of the target variable

Total_Ct_Chng_Q4_Q1 (24.56% importance):¶

  • Indicating the change in transaction count from one quarter to another is also highly predictive. Significant changes in how often a customer engages can signal changes in customer behavior, potentially leading to churn

Total_Relationship_Count (10.36% importance):¶

  • This might represent the number of different types of relationships or products a customer has with the bank
  • A higher number of relationships can increase customer stickiness, affecting churn
